<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-graphing-quadratics" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Graphing Quadratics</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.6 Graphical Methods
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                            <ul>
                              <li>Solve quadratic and cubic equations graphically</li>
                              <li>Draw graphs of circles and parabolas in different situations</li>
                            </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        15 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To show how a parabola can be constructed using a string, and to connect this visual representation to the algebraic properties of quadratics.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                    <p>
                        Make sure Learners set up the string and rulers correctly, and encourage them to observe the properties of the curve they draw.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </axiom>

        <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <alert>What you need</alert>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A piece of string (about <m>50</m> cm) and a pencil.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Two rulers / straight edges
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A tack or pin to fix the string at a point.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                We will use a string and a pencil to draw a parabola, just as in <xref ref="fig-parabola-string-setup"/>
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-parabola-string-setup">
                <caption>Drawing a Parabola with String</caption>
                <image source="images/parabola-string.jpg" width="95%">
                </image>
            </figure>
            <p>
                <alert>What to do</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Place one ruler horizontally on your paper, and mark a point <m>O</m> above the line.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Fix one end of the string at the point <m>O</m> with a tack. Tie the other end of string to the top of another ruler, which is placed vertically on top of the initial ruler. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            With a pencil, press on the string so that the pencil keeps the string tight while staying on the vertical ruler. The pencil point is <m>P</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Slide the vertical ruler along the line while keeping the string taut, tracing out a curve with the pencil.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Discuss: What shape does the curve have? How does the distance between the fixed tack <m>O</m> and the pencil compare to the distance betwen the pencil and the bottom ruler?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Challenge: Assume the fixed tack is at the origin. Try to find an equation for the curve in terms of the string length.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <exploration>
        <title>Constructing a Parabola With String</title>
        <figure xml:id="fig-parabola-string">
            <caption>Drawing A Parabola With String</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="interactive-parabola-string" platform="jsxgraph" width="90%" aspect="1:1" source="jsxgraph/parabola-string.js">
                <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-parabola-string" surface="jsxboard" aspect="1:1" width="90%"/>
                <instructions xml:id="parabola-string-instructions">
                    <p>
                        Drag the blue vertical line left and right to see how the point <m>P</m> traces out a parabola. Notice how the string segments <m>OP</m> and <m>PH</m> are always the same length.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        You can also change the length of the string with the slider, and move the focus point <m>O</m> to see how it affects the shape of the parabola.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Can you find the equation of the parabola in terms of the string length <m>L</m>? You can assume the focus point is at the origin. 
                    </p>
                </instructions>
            </interactive>
        </figure>
    </exploration>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the properties of quadratic graphs, including concavity, the axis of symmetry, and roots.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Connect the visual exploration of a parabola from the learner experience to the algebraic form of a quadratic function. Emphasize how the shape of the graph relates to the coefficients in the equation.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Mathematical Properties:</alert> Define the axis of symmetry and the vertex. Show how the roots are located symmetrically on either side of the axis of symmetry.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>


    <insight>
        <p>
            A quadratic equation in the form <md>y = ax^2 + bx + c</md> produces a curve called a <term>parabola</term>.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Properties of a Parabola:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Concavity:</term> 
                        <ul>
                            <li><p>If <m>a \gt 0</m>, the parabola opens upwards (concave up).</p></li>
                            <li><p>If <m>a \lt 0</m>, the parabola opens downwards (concave down).</p></li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Axis of Symmetry:</term> A vertical line that divides the parabola into two mirror images. Its equation is <md>x = -\frac{b}{2a}</md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Vertex:</term> The turning point of the parabola (either the minimum or maximum point). Its <m>x</m>-coordinate is on the axis of symmetry.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Roots (x-intercepts):</term> The points where the graph crosses the <m>x</m>-axis. These occur when <m>y = 0</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>y-intercept:</term> The point where the graph crosses the <m>y</m>-axis, which occurs when <m>x = 0</m>. The y-intercept is at <m>(0, c)</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <insight>
        <p> We can also graph a quadratic function in <term>factored form</term>:
            <md>y = a(x - r)(x - s)</md>
        </p>
        <p>
            In this form, we have:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Concavity:</term> Determined by the sign of <m>a</m>, just like in standard form.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Roots:</term> The roots are immediately visible as <m>r</m> and <m>s</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Axis of Symmetry:</term> The vertical line halfway between the roots, at <md>x = \frac{r + s}{2}</md>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Vertex:</term> Can be found by substituting the axis of symmetry back into the equation.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>y-intercept:</term> Found by setting <m>x = 0</m> in the equation, which gives <md>y_0 = a(-r)(-s) = ars</md>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            You should feel confortable graphing quadratics from either factored or standard form, and be able to convert between the two forms as needed by expanding or factorising.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Sketch the graph of <m>y = x^2 - 4x + 3</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Identify coefficients: <m>a = 1</m>, <m>b = -4</m>, <m>c = 3</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Concavity: Since <m>a = 1 \gt 0</m>, the parabola opens upwards.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Axis of Symmetry:
                            <md>x = -\frac{b}{2a} = -\frac{-4}{2(1)} = 2</md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Vertex: Substitute <m>x = 2</m> into the equation:
                            <md>y = (2)^2 - 4(2) + 3 = 4 - 8 + 3 = -1</md>
                            The vertex is <m>(2, -1)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Roots: Set <m>y = 0</m> and solve <m>x^2 - 4x + 3 = 0</m>:
                            <md>(x - 1)(x - 3) = 0 \Rightarrow x = 1 \text{ or } x = 3</md>
                            The roots are <m>(1, 0)</m> and <m>(3, 0)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            y-intercept: Set <m>x = 0</m>:
                            <md>y = 0^2 - 4(0) + 3 = 3</md>
                            The y-intercept is <m>(0, 3)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
                <image xml:id="img-quadratic-up" width="65%">
                    <latex-image label="fig-quadratic-up">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            axis lines=center,
                            xlabel={$x$},
                            ylabel={$y$},
                            xmin=-1, xmax=5,
                            ymin=-2, ymax=6,
                            tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                            grid=both,
                            grid style={line width=0.3pt, draw=gray!30},
                            axis equal image,
                        ]
                            \addplot[blue, thick, samples=80, smooth] {x^2 - 4*x + 3};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2.5pt, black] coordinates {(2,-1)};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.5pt, black] coordinates {(1,0) (3,0) (0,3)};
                            \node[below, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:2,-1) {Vertex $(2,-1)$};
                            \node[above left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:1,0) {$(1,0)$};
                            \node[right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:0,3) {$(0,3)$};
                            \node[above right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:3,0) {$(3,0)$};
                            \draw[dashed, red] (axis cs:2,-2) -- (axis cs:2,6) node[above, font=\footnotesize] {$x=2$};
                        \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Sketch the graph of <m>y = -x^2 + 2x + 8</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Identify coefficients: <m>a = -1</m>, <m>b = 2</m>, <m>c = 8</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Concavity: Since <m>a = -1 \lt 0</m>, the parabola opens downwards.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Axis of Symmetry:
                            <md>x = -\frac{b}{2a} = -\frac{2}{2(-1)} = 1</md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Vertex: Substitute <m>x = 1</m>:
                            <md>y = -(1)^2 + 2(1) + 8 = -1 + 2 + 8 = 9</md>
                            The vertex is <m>(1, 9)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Roots: Solve <m>-x^2 + 2x + 8 = 0</m>:
                            <md>x^2 - 2x - 8 = 0 \Rightarrow (x - 4)(x + 2) = 0 \Rightarrow x = 4 \text{ or } x = -2</md>
                            The roots are <m>(4, 0)</m> and <m>(-2, 0)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
                <image xml:id="img-quadratic-down" width="65%">
                    <latex-image label="fig-quadratic-down">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            axis lines=center,
                            xlabel={$x$},
                            ylabel={$y$},
                            xmin=-5, xmax=7,
                            ymin=-2, ymax=10,
                            tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                            grid=both,
                            grid style={line width=0.3pt, draw=gray!30},
                            axis equal image,
                            minor tick num=1
                        ]
                            \addplot[blue, thick, domain=-3:6, samples=80, smooth] {-x^2 + 2*x + 8};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2.5pt, black] coordinates {(1,9)};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.5pt, black] coordinates {(4,0) (-2,0) (0,8)};
                            \node[right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:1,9) {Vertex $(1,9)$};
                            \node[above left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:4,0) {$(4,0)$};
                            \node[above left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:-2,0) {$(-2,0)$};
                            \node[below right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:0,8) {$(0,8)$};
                            \draw[dashed, red] (axis cs:1,-2) -- (axis cs:1,10) node[above, font=\footnotesize] {$x=1$};
                        \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>Sketch the graph of <m>y = (x - 1)(x - 5)</m>. Label the roots, vertex, y-intercept, and axis of symmetry.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li><p><m>a = 1 \gt 0</m> — opens upwards.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Roots: <m>(x-1)(x-5) = 0 \Rightarrow x = 1</m> or <m>x = 5</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Axis of symmetry: midpoint of roots, <m>x = \dfrac{1+5}{2} = 3</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Vertex: substitute <m>x = 3</m> into the equation:
                        <md>y = (3-1)(3-5) = (2)(-2) = -4</md> so vertex is <m>(3,-4)</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>y-intercept: <m>y = (0-1)(0-5) = 5</m>, so <m>(0, 5)</m>.</p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <image width="90%" xml:id="factored-form">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        axis lines=center,
                        xlabel={$x$},
                        ylabel={$y$},
                        xmin=-1, xmax=7,
                        ymin=-5, ymax=7,
                        tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                        grid=both,
                        grid style={line width=0.3pt, draw=gray!30},
                        axis equal image,
                        minor tick num=1
                    ]
                        \addplot[blue, thick, domain=-0.2:6.2, samples=80, smooth] {(x-1)*(x-5)};
                        \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2.5pt, black] coordinates {(3,-4)};
                        \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.5pt, black] coordinates {(1,0) (5,0) (0,5)};
                        \node[below, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:3,-4) {$(3,-4)$};
                        \node[above right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:1,0) {$(1,0)$};
                        \node[above left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:5,0) {$(5,0)$};
                        \node[right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:0,5) {$(0,5)$};
                        \draw[dashed, red] (axis cs:3,-5) -- (axis cs:3,7) node[above, font=\footnotesize] {$x=3$};
                    \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

    <!-- <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <!-- Add STACK exercises if made -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For each of the following quadratic equations, state whether the parabola opens upwards or downwards and find the equation of the axis of symmetry:
                </p>
                <ol>
                    <li><p><m>y = x^2 + 6x + 5</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>y = -2x^2 + 8x - 3</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>y = \frac{1}{2}x^2 - 4</m></p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol>
                    <li><p>Upwards; axis of symmetry <m>x = -3</m></p></li>
                    <li><p>Downwards; axis of symmetry <m>x = 2</m></p></li>
                    <li><p>Upwards; axis of symmetry <m>x = 0</m></p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the vertex and the roots of <m>y = x^2 - 2x - 3</m>, then sketch its graph.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>Vertex: <m>(1, -4)</m>; Roots: <m>x = -1</m>, <m>x = 3</m>; y-intercept: <m>(0, -3)</m>.</p>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            axis lines=center,
                            xlabel={$x$},
                            ylabel={$y$},
                            xmin=-2, xmax=4,
                            ymin=-5, ymax=2,
                            tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                            grid=both,
                            grid style={line width=0.3pt, draw=gray!30},
                            axis equal image,
                            minor tick num=1
                        ]
                            \addplot[blue, thick, domain=-2:4, samples=80, smooth] {x^2 - 2*x - 3};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2.5pt, black] coordinates {(1,-4)};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.5pt, black] coordinates {(-1,0) (3,0) (0,-3)};
                            \node[below, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:1,-4) {$(1,-4)$};
                            \node[above right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:-1,0) {$(-1,0)$};
                            \node[above left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:3,0) {$(3,0)$};
                            \node[left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:0,-3) {$(0,-3)$};
                            \draw[dashed, red] (axis cs:1,-5) -- (axis cs:1,2) node[above, font=\footnotesize] {$x=1$};
                        \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A quadratic graph has roots at <m>x = -2</m> and <m>x = 4</m>. What is the equation of its axis of symmetry?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p><m>x = 1</m> (The axis of symmetry is halfway between the roots: <m>\frac{-2+4}{2} = 1</m>).</p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Find the properties and sketch the graph of <m>y = 2x^2 + 4x</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><p>Concavity: Opens up (<m>a = 2 \gt 0</m>).</p></li>
                            <li><p>Axis of Symmetry: <m>x = -\frac{4}{2(2)} = -1</m>.</p></li>
                            <li><p>Vertex: <m>y = 2(-1)^2 + 4(-1) = 2 - 4 = -2</m>. Vertex is <m>(-1, -2)</m>.</p></li>
                            <li><p>Roots: <m>2x^2 + 4x = 0 \Rightarrow 2x(x + 2) = 0 \Rightarrow x = 0 \text{ or } x = -2</m>.</p></li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                    <image xml:id="img-quadratic-narrow" width="65%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[
                                axis lines=center,
                                xlabel={$x$},
                                ylabel={$y$},
                                xmin=-4, xmax=2,
                                ymin=-3, ymax=5,
                                tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                                grid=both,
                                grid style={line width=0.3pt, draw=gray!30},
                                axis equal image,
                            ]
                                \addplot[blue, thick, domain=-2.8:0.8, samples=80, smooth] {2*x^2 + 4*x};
                                \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2.5pt, black] coordinates {(-1,-2)};
                                \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.5pt, black] coordinates {(0,0) (-2,0)};
                                \node[below, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:-1,-2) {$(-1,-2)$};
                                \node[above right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:0,0) {$(0,0)$};
                                \node[above left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:-2,0) {$(-2,0)$};
                                \draw[dashed, red] (axis cs:-1,-3) -- (axis cs:-1,5) node[above, font=\footnotesize] {$x=-1$};
                            \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </solution>
            </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>Sketch the graph of <m>y = -(x + 1)(x - 3)</m>. Label the roots, vertex, y-intercept, and axis of symmetry.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>The leading coefficient is <m>-1 \lt 0</m>, so the parabola opens downwards.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Roots: <m>-(x+1)(x-3) = 0 \Rightarrow x = -1</m> or <m>x = 3</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Axis of symmetry: <m>x = \dfrac{-1+3}{2} = 1</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Vertex: <m>y = -(1+1)(1-3) = -(2)(-2) = 4</m>, so vertex is <m>(1, 4)</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>y-intercept: <m>y = -(0+1)(0-3) = 3</m>, so <m>(0, 3)</m>.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            axis lines=center,
                            xlabel={$x$},
                            ylabel={$y$},
                            xmin=-3, xmax=5,
                            ymin=-2, ymax=5,
                            tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                            grid=both,
                            grid style={line width=0.3pt, draw=gray!30},
                            axis equal image,
                        ]
                            \addplot[blue, thick, domain=-1.4:3.4, samples=80, smooth] {-(x+1)*(x-3)};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2.5pt, black] coordinates {(1,4)};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.5pt, black] coordinates {(-1,0) (3,0) (0,3)};
                            \node[above, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:1,4) {$(1,4)$};
                            \node[above left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:-1,0) {$(-1,0)$};
                            \node[above right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:3,0) {$(3,0)$};
                            \node[left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:0,3) {$(0,3)$};
                            \draw[dashed, red] (axis cs:1,-2) -- (axis cs:1,5) node[above, font=\footnotesize] {$x=1$};
                        \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>Sketch the graph of <m>y = x^2 + 2x - 8</m>. Label the roots, vertex, y-intercept, and axis of symmetry.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Since <m>a = 1 \gt 0</m>, the parabola opens upwards.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Axis of symmetry: <m>x = -\dfrac{2}{2(1)} = -1</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Vertex: <m>y = (-1)^2 + 2(-1) - 8 = 1 - 2 - 8 = -9</m>, so vertex is <m>(-1, -9)</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Roots: <m>x^2 + 2x - 8 = (x+4)(x-2) = 0 \Rightarrow x = -4</m> or <m>x = 2</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>y-intercept: <m>y = 0 + 0 - 8 = -8</m>, so <m>(0, -8)</m>.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            axis lines=center,
                            xlabel={$x$},
                            ylabel={$y$},
                            xmin=-8, xmax=6,
                            ymin=-10, ymax=3,
                            tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                            grid=both,
                            grid style={line width=0.3pt, draw=gray!30},
                            axis equal image,
                        ]
                            \addplot[blue, thick, domain=-5:4, samples=80, smooth] {x^2 + 2*x - 8};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2.5pt, black] coordinates {(-1,-9)};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.5pt, black] coordinates {(-4,0) (2,0) (0,-8)};
                            \node[below, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:-1,-9) {$(-1,-9)$};
                            \node[above left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:-4,0) {$(-4,0)$};
                            \node[above right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:2,0) {$(2,0)$};
                            \node[right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:0,-8) {$(0,-8)$};
                            \draw[dashed, red] (axis cs:-1,-10) -- (axis cs:-1,3) node[above left, font=\footnotesize] {$x=-1$};
                        \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>Sketch the graph of <m>y = 2(x - 1)(x - 3)</m>. Label the roots, vertex, y-intercept, and axis of symmetry.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Since <m>a = 2 \gt 0</m>, the parabola opens upwards.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Roots: <m>2(x-1)(x-3) = 0 \Rightarrow x = 1</m> or <m>x = 3</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Axis of symmetry: midpoint of roots, <m>x = \dfrac{1+3}{2} = 2</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Vertex: <m>y = 2(2-1)(2-3) = 2(1)(-1) = -2</m>, so vertex is <m>(2, -2)</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>y-intercept: <m>y = 2(0-1)(0-3) = 6</m>, so <m>(0, 6)</m>.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            axis lines=center,
                            xlabel={$x$},
                            ylabel={$y$},
                            xmin=-2, xmax=6,
                            ymin=-3, ymax=8,
                            tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                            grid=both,
                            grid style={line width=0.3pt, draw=gray!30},
                            axis equal image,
                        ]
                            \addplot[blue, thick, domain=-2:6, samples=80, smooth] {2*(x-1)*(x-3)};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2.5pt, black] coordinates {(2,-2)};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.5pt, black] coordinates {(1,0) (3,0) (0,6)};
                            \node[below, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:2,-2) {$(2,-2)$};
                            \node[above left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:1,0) {$(1,0)$};
                            \node[above right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:3,0) {$(3,0)$};
                            \node[right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:0,6) {$(0,6)$};
                            \draw[dashed, red] (axis cs:2,-3) -- (axis cs:2,8) node[above, font=\footnotesize] {$x=2$};
                        \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The graph of a quadratic function is shown below. Find its equation.
                </p>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            axis lines=center,
                            xlabel={$x$},
                            ylabel={$y$},
                            xmin=-1, xmax=5,
                            ymin=-5, ymax=3,
                            tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                            grid=both,
                            grid style={line width=0.3pt, draw=gray!30},
                            axis equal image,
                        ]
                            \addplot[blue, thick, domain=-0.6:4.6, samples=80, smooth] {x^2 - 4*x};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.5pt, black] coordinates {(0,0) (4,0)};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2.5pt, black] coordinates {(2,-4)};
                            \node[above right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:0,0) {$(0,0)$};
                            \node[above left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:4,0) {$(4,0)$};
                            \node[below right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:2,-4) {$(2,-4)$};
                        \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p><m>y = x(x - 4) = x^2 - 4x</m></p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The roots are at <m>x = 0</m> and <m>x = 4</m>, so write <m>y = a \cdot x(x - 4)</m>.
                    Substitute the vertex <m>(2, -4)</m> to find <m>a</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>-4 \amp= a(2)(2 - 4) = -4a</mrow>
                        <mrow>a \amp= 1</mrow>
                    </md>
                    The equation is <m>y = x(x - 4)</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The graph of a quadratic function is shown below. Find its equation.
                </p>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            axis lines=center,
                            xlabel={$x$},
                            ylabel={$y$},
                            xmin=-5, xmax=3,
                            ymin=-5, ymax=4,
                            tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                            grid=both,
                            grid style={line width=0.3pt, draw=gray!30},
                            axis equal image,
                        ]
                            \addplot[blue, thick, samples=80, smooth] {(x+3)*(x-1)};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.5pt, black] coordinates {(-3,0) (1,0) (0,-3)};
                            \node[above left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:-3,0) {$(-3,0)$};
                            \node[above right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:1,0) {$(1,0)$};
                            \node[right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:0,-3) {$(0,-3)$};
                        \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p><m>y = (x + 3)(x - 1)</m></p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The roots are at <m>x = -3</m> and <m>x = 1</m>, so write <m>y = a(x + 3)(x - 1)</m>.
                    Substitute the y-intercept <m>(0, -3)</m> to find <m>a</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>-3 \amp= a(0 + 3)(0 - 1) = -3a</mrow>
                        <mrow>a \amp= 1</mrow>
                    </md>
                    The equation is <m>y = (x + 3)(x - 1) = x^2 + 2x - 3</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The graph of a quadratic function is shown below. Find its equation.
                </p>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            axis lines=center,
                            xlabel={$x$},
                            ylabel={$y$},
                            xmin=-7, xmax=5,
                            ymin=-3, ymax=10,
                            tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                            grid=both,
                            grid style={line width=0.3pt, draw=gray!30},
                            axis equal image,
                        ]
                            \addplot[blue, thick, samples=80, smooth] {-(x+4)*(x-2)};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.5pt, black] coordinates {(-4,0) (2,0) (0,8)};
                            \node[above left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:-4,0) {$(-4,0)$};
                            \node[above right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:2,0) {$(2,0)$};
                            \node[right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:0,8) {$(0,8)$};
                        \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p><m>y = -(x + 4)(x - 2)</m></p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The roots are at <m>x = -4</m> and <m>x = 2</m>, so write <m>y = a(x + 4)(x - 2)</m>.
                    Substitute the y-intercept <m>(0, 8)</m> to find <m>a</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>8 \amp= a(0 + 4)(0 - 2) = -8a</mrow>
                        <mrow>a \amp= -1</mrow>
                    </md>
                    The equation is <m>y = -(x + 4)(x - 2)</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The graph of a quadratic function is shown below. Find its equation.
                </p>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            axis lines=center,
                            xlabel={$x$},
                            ylabel={$y$},
                            xmin=-6, xmax=8,
                            ymin=-5, ymax=10,
                            tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                            grid=both,
                            grid style={line width=0.3pt, draw=gray!30},
                            axis equal image,
                        ]
                            \addplot[blue, thick, samples=80, smooth] {-2*(x+1)*(x-3)};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.5pt, black] coordinates {(-1,0) (3,0) (0,6)};
                            \node[above left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:-1,0) {$(-1,0)$};
                            \node[above right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:3,0) {$(3,0)$};
                            \node[left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:0,6) {$(0,6)$};
                        \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p><m>y = -2(x + 1)(x - 3)</m></p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The roots are at <m>x = -1</m> and <m>x = 3</m>, so write <m>y = a(x + 1)(x - 3)</m>.
                    Substitute the y-intercept <m>(0, 6)</m> to find <m>a</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>6 \amp= a(0 + 1)(0 - 3) = -3a</mrow>
                        <mrow>a \amp= -2</mrow>
                    </md>
                    The equation is <m>y = -2(x + 1)(x - 3)</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>


        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    This exercise develops a useful alternative form of the quadratic formula.
                    Consider a quadratic equation <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m> with two roots <m>r</m> and <m>s</m>.
                </p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Divide every term by <m>a</m> to rewrite the equation in the form
                            <md>x^2 + Bx + P = 0</md>
                            State the values of <m>B</m> and <m>P</m> in terms of <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Since <m>r</m> and <m>s</m> are the roots, the equation can also be written in factored form as <m>(x - r)(x - s) = 0</m>.
                            Expand this factored form and compare coefficients with <m>x^2 + Bx + P</m> to show that
                            <md>
                                <mrow>r + s \amp= -B = -\frac{b}{a} \quad \text{(sum of roots)}</mrow>
                                <mrow>rs \amp= P = \frac{c}{a} \quad \text{(product of roots)}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>m = \dfrac{r + s}{2}</m> be the average of the roots, and let <m>d</m> be the distance from <m>m</m> to each root, so that <md>r = m - d \text{ and } s = m + d</md>, as shown below:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <image width="68%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[
                                        axis lines=center,
                                        xlabel={$x$},
                                        ylabel={$y$},
                                        xmin=-0.5, xmax=6.5,
                                        ymin=-3.5, ymax=3.5,
                                        xticklabels={},
                                        yticklabels={},
                                        grid=both,
                                        grid style={line width=0.3pt, draw=gray!30},
                                        axis equal image,
                                    ]
                                        \addplot[blue, very thick, domain=-0.3:6.3, samples=60, smooth] {0.5*(x-1)*(x-5)};
                                        \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2.5pt, black] coordinates {(1,0) (5,0)};
                                        \node[below=6pt, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:1,0) {$r$};
                                        \node[below=6pt, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:5,0) {$s$};
                                        \draw[thick] (axis cs:3,0.1) -- (axis cs:3,-0.1);
                                        \node[below=6pt, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:3,0) {$m$};
                                        \draw[&lt;-&gt;, thick, red!80!black] (axis cs:1,0.7) -- (axis cs:3,0.7)
                                            node[midway, below, font=\footnotesize] {$d$};
                                        \draw[&lt;-&gt;, thick, red!80!black] (axis cs:3,0.7) -- (axis cs:5,0.7)
                                            node[midway, below, font=\footnotesize] {$d$};
                                    \end{axis}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </p>
                        <ol marker="(i)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Use part (b) to show that <m>m = -\dfrac{b}{2a}</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Substitute <m>r = m - d</m> and <m>s = m + d</m> into <m>rs = \dfrac{c}{a}</m> to show that
                                    <md>d^2 = m^2 - \frac{c}{a}.</md>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Let <m>p = \dfrac{c}{a}</m>.
                                    Explain why the roots of the quadratic can be written as
                                    <md>x = m \pm \sqrt{m^2 - p}.</md>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Use <m>x = m \pm \sqrt{m^2 - p}</m> to solve <m>x^2 + 6x + 7 = 0</m>.
                            Leave your answer in surd form.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Sketch the graph of <m>y = x^2 + 6x + 7</m>. Mark the roots <m>r</m> and <m>s</m>, the midpoint <m>m</m> on the <m>x</m>-axis, and the distances <m>d</m> from <m>m</m> to each root.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Compare the two quadratic formulae:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> x \amp = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} </mrow>
                                <mrow> x \amp = m \pm \sqrt{m^2 - p} </mrow>
                            </md>
                            Which do you prefer? What are the advantages and disadvantages of each formula?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Dividing <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m> by <m>a</m>:
                            <md>x^2 + \frac{b}{a}x + \frac{c}{a} = 0</md>
                            so <m>B = \dfrac{b}{a}</m> and <m>P = \dfrac{c}{a}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Expanding the factored form:
                            <md>(x - r)(x - s) = x^2 - (r + s)x + rs</md>
                            Comparing with <m>x^2 + Bx + P</m> coefficient by coefficient: the coefficient of <m>x</m> gives <m>-(r + s) = B</m>, so
                            <md>r + s = -B = -\frac{b}{a},</md>
                            and the constant term gives
                            <md>rs = P = \frac{c}{a}.</md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <ol marker="(i)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Using <m>r + s = -\dfrac{b}{a}</m>:
                                    <md>m = \frac{r + s}{2} = \frac{-b/a}{2} = -\frac{b}{2a}</md>
                                    This is the axis of symmetry of the parabola.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Substituting <m>r = m - d</m> and <m>s = m + d</m>:
                                    <md>rs = (m - d)(m + d) = m^2 - d^2</md>
                                    From part (b), <m>rs = \dfrac{c}{a}</m>, so <m>m^2 - d^2 = \dfrac{c}{a}</m>, giving
                                    <md>d^2 = m^2 - \frac{c}{a}.</md>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Since <m>d = \sqrt{m^2 - p}</m>, and the roots satisfy <m>r = m - d</m> and <m>s = m + d</m>, both roots are given by
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow> x \amp = m \pm d </mrow>
                                        <mrow> x \amp = m \pm \sqrt{m^2 - p} </mrow>
                                    </md>
                                    where <m>m = -\dfrac{b}{2a}</m> is the average of the roots and <m>p = \dfrac{c}{a}</m> is the product of the roots.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For <m>x^2 + 6x + 7 = 0</m>, the equation is already normalised, with <m>B = 6</m> and <m>p = 7</m>.
                            <md>
                                <mrow>m \amp= -\frac{6}{2} = -3</mrow>
                                <mrow>d \amp= \sqrt{m^2 - p} </mrow> 
                                <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{(-3)^2 - 7} </mrow> 
                                <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{9 - 7} </mrow> 
                                <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{2}</mrow>
                            </md>
                            Therefore <m>x = -3 \pm \sqrt{2}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We draw the graph with line of symmetry at <m>x = m = -3</m>, and the roots at <m>r = -3 - \sqrt{2}</m> and <m>s = -3 + \sqrt{2}</m>.
                        </p>
                        <image width="78%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[
                                    axis lines=center,
                                    xlabel={$x$},
                                    ylabel={$y$},
                                    xmin=-9, xmax=3,
                                    ymin=-3, ymax=8,
                                    tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                                    grid=both,
                                    grid style={line width=0.3pt, draw=gray!30},
                                    axis equal image,
                                    minor tick num=1,
                                ]
                                    \addplot[blue, very thick, domain=-7:1, samples=80, smooth] {x^2 + 6*x + 7};
                                    \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2.5pt, black] coordinates {(-4.414,0) (-1.586,0) (-3,-2)};
                                    \node[above left, xshift=-5pt, yshift=1pt, fill=white, opacity=0.7, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:-4.414,0) {$r = -3-\sqrt{2}$};
                                    \node[above right, xshift=2pt, yshift=1pt, fill=white, opacity=0.7, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:-1.586,0) {$s = -3+\sqrt{2}$};
                                    \node[below left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:-3,-2) {$(-3,-2)$};
                                    \draw[dashed, thick, gray!80] (axis cs:-3,-3) -- (axis cs:-3,8);
                                    \node[font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:-3,4) {$m = -3$};
                                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;, thick, red!80!black] (axis cs:-4.414,0.5) -- (axis cs:-3,0.5)
                                        node[midway, above, font=\footnotesize] {$\sqrt{2}$};
                                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;, thick, red!80!black] (axis cs:-3,0.5) -- (axis cs:-1.586,0.5)
                                        node[midway, above, font=\footnotesize] {$\sqrt{2}$};
                                \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <title>A Race in the Field</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Two people are playing a game. <alert>Person A</alert> stands at a fixed point in the middle of a field. <alert>Person B</alert> stands somewhere along a road that runs along one edge of the field. Both people run at exactly the same speed.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The rules are:
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Someone suggests a point <m>P</m> in the field.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Person A runs from their fixed position to <m>P</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Person B may start from <em>any</em> position along the road before running to <m>P</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Whoever arrives first claims the point.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Set up coordinates so that the road lies along the <m>x</m>-axis and Person A stands at the point <m>(0, 4)</m>.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-race-field-setup">
                    <caption>The field. Person A is at <m>(0, 4)</m>; the road runs along the <m>x</m>-axis.</caption>
                    <image width="75%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[
                                axis lines=center,
                                xlabel={Road},
                                ylabel={},
                                xmin=-8, xmax=8,
                                ymin=-1, ymax=8,
                                tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                                grid=both,
                                grid style={line width=0.3pt, draw=gray!30},
                                xtick={-6,-4,-2,2,4,6},
                                ytick={1,2,3,4,5,6,7},
                                width=10cm, height=8cm,
                            ]
                                \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=3.5pt, red] coordinates {(0,4)};
                                \node[right, font=\small, red] at (axis cs:0.2,4) {$A$};
                            \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Choose some points in the field and mark them on your diagram. For each one, work out who wins the race to that point — A or B.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <em>Hint: B's distance is just the vertical height of the point above the road. You can use a ruler to measure A's distance directly from the diagram.</em>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Can you find any points where the race is a tie? Try to find more than one.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>P = (x, y)</m> be a general point in the field.
                        </p>
                        <ol marker="(i)">
                            <li><p>Write an expression for A's distance to <m>P</m>.</p></li>
                            <li><p>B will always choose the best possible starting position on the road. Explain why B's shortest distance to <m>P</m> is equal to <m>y</m>.</p></li>
                            <li><p>Write an equation whose solutions are exactly the tie points.</p></li>
                        </ol>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Simplify your equation from (b)(iii) to find the equation of the boundary between A's territory and B's territory. What shape is the boundary?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Sketch the boundary on your diagram and shade A's region and B's region in different colours.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Look back at the string activity at the start of this section. Compare the curve you drew then with the boundary you have just found. What do you notice? What role does Person A play in the string construction? What role does the road play?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><alert>(a)</alert></p>
                <p>
                    For any point <m>P = (x, y)</m>, A's distance is <m>\sqrt{x^2 + (y-4)^2}</m> and B's best distance is <m>y</m> (running straight from the road up to <m>P</m>). Some examples:
                </p>
                <tabular halign="center" top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                    <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                        <cell>Point <m>P</m></cell>
                        <cell>A's distance</cell>
                        <cell>B's distance</cell>
                        <cell>Winner</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>(0, 1)</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                        <cell>B</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>(0, 3)</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                        <cell>A</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>(4, 3)</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\sqrt{17} \approx 4.12</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                        <cell>B</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>(4, 5)</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\sqrt{17} \approx 4.12</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                        <cell>A</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>(0, 2)</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                        <cell>Tie</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>(4, 4)</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                        <cell>Tie</cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
                <p>
                    The two tie points above — <m>(0, 2)</m> and <m>(4, 4)</m> — both lie on the boundary found in part (c). Students who use a ruler on the diagram may find these or other tie points by trial and error.
                </p>
                <p><alert>(b)</alert></p>
                <ol marker="(i)">
                    <li>
                        <p>A's distance to <m>P = (x, y)</m>:
                            <md>\sqrt{x^2 + (y - 4)^2}.</md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            B's best starting position is the point on the road directly below <m>P</m>, namely <m>(x, 0)</m>. Running straight up from there, B travels a distance of <m>y</m>. Any other starting position would require B to travel diagonally, which is longer.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The tie condition is:
                            <md>\sqrt{x^2 + (y - 4)^2} = y.</md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                <p><alert>(c)</alert></p>
                <p>
                    Squaring both sides (both sides are positive for points above the road):
                    <md>
                        <mrow>x^2 + (y - 4)^2 \amp= y^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>x^2 + y^2 - 8y + 16 \amp= y^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>x^2 \amp= 8y - 16</mrow>
                        <mrow>x^2 \amp= 8(y - 2)</mrow>
                    </md>
                    This is a <em>parabola</em>, with vertex at <m>(0, 2)</m>, opening upwards.
                </p>
                <p><alert>(d)</alert></p>
                <image width="75%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            axis lines=center,
                            xlabel={Road},
                            ylabel={},
                            xmin=-8, xmax=8,
                            ymin=-1, ymax=8,
                            tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                            grid=both,
                            grid style={line width=0.3pt, draw=gray!30},
                            xtick={-6,-4,-2,2,4,6},
                            ytick={1,2,3,4,5,6,7},
                            width=10cm, height=8cm,
                        ]
                            \addplot[red!70!black, very thick, domain=-7.5:7.5, samples=120, smooth] {x^2/8 + 2};
                            \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=3.5pt, red] coordinates {(0,4)};
                            \node[right, font=\small, red] at (axis cs:0.2,4) {$A$};
                            \node[font=\small, blue!70!black] at (axis cs:0,1) {\textbf{B's region}};
                            \node[font=\small, red!70!black] at (axis cs:0,6.8) {\textbf{A's region}};
                            \node[font=\footnotesize, red!70!black, right] at (axis cs:5,5.2) {$x^2 = 8(y-2)$};
                        \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                <p>
                    Points above the parabola are closer to A than to the road — A wins there. Points below the parabola are closer to the road than to A — B wins there.
                </p>
                <p><alert>(e)</alert></p>
                <p>
                    The boundary is exactly the parabola from the string activity. In that construction, the pencil was always kept at equal distance from the tack point and from the ruler — which is the same as the tie condition in the race. Person A plays the role of the tack: a fixed point in the interior. The road plays the role of the ruler: the fixed line whose distance is being matched. The parabola is the set of all points equally close to A and to the road.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

    </exercises>

    <!-- [LP] Add information on how to differentiate  -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Provide tables of values to help plot points before identifying patterns. Use graphing software to see how changing <m>a, b, c</m> affects the graph.
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>The core lesson activities as described above, focusing on the relationship between the algebraic form and the geometric features.</line>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Investigate how many roots a quadratic can have (0, 1, or 2) and how this relates to the vertex's position and concavity. Introduce the discriminant.
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>

